article.headline: Tennessee shoots a dismal 28 percent
article.linkText: Upset at home: No. 5  Lady Vols
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The only thing that annoyed coach Pat
Summitt as much as Tennessee's horrible offense was its bad
defense.

"We missed a lot of easy shots," she said after the Lady Vols (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) were beaten 59-57 by Duke (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) on
Thursday night.

The Lady Vols shot 28 percent (21-of-75) and lost at home for
only the 14th time since Thompson-Boling Arena opened in 1987.
Monique Currie scored 20 points for the Blue Devils (6-1), who made
the Tennessee defense appear porous.

Currie's final basket -- from a wide-open lane -- was the most
alarming to Summitt.

"All I can say is you've got to cover the basketball especially
when one of the best players on the floor has it in her hands,"
she said. "Our defense really let us down at various times."

Tennessee (4-2) shot poorly for a third straight game, looked
weak in the post and was outrebounded 53-42.

"I can't say I've been in a situation like this for an extended
period of time," Summitt said. "We'll learn from this. We have a
lot of opportunities."

Duke coach Gail Goestenkors believes her team has plenty of room
for improvement.

"I think both teams are still trying to find their way
offensively," she said. "I think that showed tonight.

"I know both teams will continue to improve, and I think we
both learned a lot about our teams from this game."

But on this night, the Blue Devils appeared just fine after
losing last season's top seniors, Alana Beard and Iciss Tillis.

The go-to player now is Currie, who scored 16 of her points in
the second half and had nine rebounds.

She had six points in the final 1:41 as Duke became only the
seventh visiting team to win at Thompson-Boling. Besides Duke and
Connecticut, which won here last season, the Lady Vols have dropped
games to Texas, Louisiana Tech, Auburn, Georgia and Stanford.

Mistie Williams added 14 points and 10 rebounds for her third
double-double this season, and Jessica Foley had 11 points for the
Blue Devils.

The lead changed hands several times down the stretch, but the
Blue Devils made baskets when they needed them.

Currie converted two free throws to put Duke ahead 55-53, but
Tye'sha Fluker made a putback to tie it. Currie made a jumper at
the other end, but Shyra Ely scored on a putback to tie it at 57
with 47.9 seconds left.

At the other end, Currie drove to the basket for an easy layup
that put the Blue Devils ahead for good.

Williams then missed a free throw, but Shanna Zolman missed two
3-pointers in the final 13 seconds.

Zolman scored 17 of her 19 points after halftime, and Ely
finished with 15 points and eight rebounds.

Tennessee leads the series 4-3 after the teams' first meeting in
Knoxville.

The Lady Vols led by as many as six points in the second half
after going on a 10-4 run out of the break. Duke responded with a
10-3 run that included eight points by Foley to retake the lead
with 12:09 remaining.

Tennessee shot 32 percent in its recent win against Temple and
33 percent a week ago in a loss at Texas that dropped the Lady Vols
from the No. 1 spot. Duke has held four opponents this season to
less than 30-percent shooting.
